{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f0a4b41f-04a0-432e-910b-d662ebe8c1d8","content":"## Diagnosis\n\n.NET MAUI's Android workload **bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17**. When you set `JAVA_HOME` to an external JDK (like Temurin), it overrides the expected JDK and the build's version-string parser can fail on Temurin's non-standard version output.\n\n## Fix\n\n**Option A — Let MAUI use its bundled JDK (recommended):**\n\nUnset `JAVA_HOME` before building:\n\n```bash\nunset JAVA_HOME\ndotnet build\n```\n\nRemove or comment out any `export JAVA_HOME=…` line in your `~/.zshrc` / `~/.bash_profile` if you want a permanent fix.\n\n**Option B — Point to the Microsoft OpenJDK that the workload installed:**\n\n```bash\n# Find the bundled JDK:\nls ~/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/\n\n# Then set JAVA_HOME to it, e.g.:\nexport JAVA_HOME=\"$HOME/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/microsoft_dist_openjdk_17.0.12\"\n```\n\n**Option C — Set it per-project in your `.csproj`:**\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>$(HOME)/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/microsoft_dist_openjdk_17.0.12</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** The Temurin JDK itself is fine for general Java work, but .NET MAUI Android expects the Microsoft-distributed OpenJDK it ships with. Unset `JAVA_HOME` and the build will find the right one automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fa12c8b7-00b6-4d91-8668-15f7664f512c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed on macOS. Let me think about what the common issue is here.\n\nThis is a well-known issue: .NET MAUI (and Xamarin.Android) Android builds require a specific JDK. Starting with .NET 8, the Android SDK workload bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17 distribution, and the build system expects to use that. However, having JAVA_HOME pointing to a different JDK can cause issues.\n\nBut more specifically, the common issue with .NET MAUI Android builds on macOS with JDK 17 is related to the fact that:\n\n\nThe most likely culprit is either a version mismatch between the JDK being used and what the build tools expect, or JAVA_HOME pointing to the wrong location entirely. The build could be throwing a `UnsupportedClassVersionError` if it's picking up an incompatible JDK, or the Android SDK tools might not be finding the right Java installation at all. with their own JDK (Microsoft OpenJDK 17) and there can be conflicts when `JAVA_HOME` is set to a different JDK.\n\nAnother very common issue: On macOS, the Adoptium Temurin JDK installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, but the .NET Android build expects the JDK at the Microsoft OpenJDK location.\n\nThe most likely culprit here is that .NET MAUI/Android builds since .NET 8 bundle Microsoft's OpenJDK 17, and when `JAVA_HOME` points to an external JDK like Temurin, it either overrides the expected path or the build ignores it entirely and can't find the bundled version. The specific error is probably something like \"Could not determine the Java version from 'java -version'\" when the JDK vendor string doesn't match what MSBuild expects, or possibly a version mismatch between Temurin 17.0.12 and what the Android Gradle plugin or d8/r8 tooling requires. I'm thinking the real issue is likely in the .NET Android build validation step that checks the Java version. The .NET Android build system ships its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17, and when you override `JAVA_HOME` to point to Temurin instead, it can cause parsing failures or incompatibilities. The practical solution is to either unset `JAVA_HOME` entirely so .NET MAUI uses its bundled JDK, or configure it to point to the Microsoft OpenJDK installation that .NET provides. either unsetting `JAVA_HOME` to let the build use the bundled JDK, or pointing it to the Microsoft OpenJDK distribution that comes with the .NET Android workload. The core issue is that .NET MAUI for Android ships with its own JDK, so overriding it with a different distribution like Temurin often causes compatibility problems.","outputTokens":1959,"requestId":"9BD1:13440B:6205638:6D35167:69EC0EC3"},"id":"fbac52cf-09a8-463a-a7de-39d2d6c373c7","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:46:33.758Z","parentId":"4bbf4d23-d798-4259-98e0-6c2acbd551c6"}
